'''Northern Kentucky University''' is a [[state university (U.S.)|public]], [[co-educational]] [[university]] located in [[Highland Heights, Kentucky]], seven miles (11 km) southeast of [[Cincinnati, Ohio]].  Enrollment is currently about 14,200 students. NKU is the second largest university in [[Cincinnati-Hamilton, OH-KY-IN Metropolitan Statistical Area|Greater Cincinnati]] and the youngest of Kentucky's eight state universities.

==History==
Northern Kentucky University was founded in 1968 as Northern Kentucky State College and awarded its first bachelor's degrees in May 1973.  Originally formed as a [[University of Kentucky]] extension campus, in 1976, it became Northern Kentucky University. The [http://chaselaw.nku.edu/ Salmon P. Chase College of Law], formerly an independent law school in Cincinnati, merged with Northern Kentucky State College in 1971. The newest college at NKU is the  [http://informatics.nku.edu/ College of Informatics], founded in 2006.

==Campuses==
[[Image:Northern Kentucky University.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Northern Kentucky University, Highland Heights Campus.]]
 

NKU's main campus in [[Highland Heights, Kentucky]] is situated on more than 330 acres of rolling countryside along [[US 27]], just off [[Interstate 275 (Ohio)|I-275]], seven miles (11 km) southeast of [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]].

NKU's [http://edoutreach.nku.edu/Covington%20Campus%20Main%20Page.htm Covington campus], located in [[Covington, Kentucky]], mainly serves nontraditional and adult students and also hosts the Program for Adult-Centered Education and Emergency Medical Technology programs.

The [http://www.nku.edu/~grantcounty/ NKU Grant County Center], located in [[Williamstown, Kentucky]] is a partnership between the Grant County Foundation for Higher Education and NKU. It houses NKU educational programs and the Williamstown Innovation Center.

==Campus life==

NKU is in the process of building a $37 million, {{convert|144000|sqft|sqm|-2|sing=on}} student union building, the $60 million Bank of Kentucky Center, a 9,000-to-10,000-seat arena for basketball games and other events, and a $30 million four-story complex featuring a 100-room hotel, a {{convert|40000|sqft|sqm|-3|sing=on}}, upscale restaurant and retail area and {{convert|30000|sqft|sqm|-3}} of office space.

NKU's Alumni Association Lecture Series has featured such guests as politicians Mario Cuomo, Alan Keyes, Steve Forbes, Newt Gingrich, George McGovern, Bob Dole and John Edwards; political strategists James Carville, Mary Matalin and Paul Begala; journalist Bob Woodward; and commentators George Stephanopoulos, George Will, Tucker Carlson, and Al Franken. The 2007 Alumni Association Lecture Series will feature former Republican political candidate and conservative polemicist Pat Buchanan and former Senate Majority Leader, Democrat Tom Daschle.

